  "languageSpontaneousSpeechTitle": "Spontaneous Speech",
  "languageSpontaneousSpeechExaminerInstruction": "Evaluate free speech by listening for impairments of fluency, articulation and the presence of paraphasias. Paraphasias are word substitutions and can be phonemic i.e. \"sitter\" for \"sister\" or semantic i.e. \"jug\" for \"glass.\"",

  "languageComprehensionThreeStageTitle": "Comprehension",
  "languageComprehensionThreeStageExaminerInstruction": "Evaluate comprehension by using a 3-stage command. Intact basic comprehension ensures good compliance with any test procedures that follow.",
  "languageComprehensionThreeStagePatientInstruction": "\"Can you point with your finger to the ceiling, the floor and the door.\"",
  "languageComprehensionThreeStageResponseNormal": "3 stages complete without an error",
  "languageComprehensionThreeStageResponseEquivocal": "Some difficulty",
  "languageComprehensionThreeStageResponseImpaired": "1 or more clear errors",

  "languageComprehensionMovingObjectsTitle": "Comprehension: Moving 3 Objects Task",
  "languageComprehensionMovingObjectsExaminerInstruction": "Place 3 objects in front of the patient and name them while they are being placed to exclude naming ability and object agnosia as confounding factors. Common objects such as a coin, keys and a piece of paper can be used. Begin with simple commands and then move to more complex instructions.",
  "languageComprehensionMovingObjectsPatientInstruction1": "\"Turn the coin over\"",
  "languageComprehensionMovingObjectsPatientInstruction2": "\"Place the keys on the other side of the paper\"",
  "languageComprehensionMovingObjectsPatientInstruction3": "\"Place the coin between the keys and the paper, and then turn over the paper.\"",

  "languageRepetitionTitle": "Repetition",
  "languageRepetitionExaminerInstruction": "Ask the patient to repeat the following.",
  "languageRepetitionPatientInstruction1": "\"No ifs ands or buts.\"",
  "languageRepetitionPatientInstruction2": "\"The little boy went to the shopping mall to spend his money.\"",

  "languageNamingTitle": "Naming",

  "languageObjectNamingTitle": "Naming",
  "languageObjectNamingExaminerInstruction": "Point towards the following objects and ask the patient to name it. Inability to name objects (nominal dysphasia) must be distinguished from visual object agnosia.",
  "languageObjectNamingPatientInstruction": "\"Can you tell me what this is?\"",
  "languageObjectNamingCommonObjects": "Point to a watch, pen, tissue, button, shoe, and shirt.",
  "languageObjectNamingUncommonObjects": "Less common objects are: knuckles, ring finger, eyebrow, winder of a watch, and collar.",
  "languageObjectNamingDistinguishInstruction": "To distinguish between nominal aphasia and visual object agnosia, ask the patient to describe the object or its use. If this can be done adequately then visual perception might be normal and the deficit is more likely language based. Language deficits can be further examined by providing the patient with language cues by saying either a part of the word or giving a phonetic clue. For example, say \"col...\" for collar or say it sounds like \"dollar\" Some patients may then be able to progress and say the word, the deficit is then more likely to be nominal aphasia.",

  "languagePictureNamingTitle": "Picture Naming",
  "languagePictureNamingPatientInstruction": "\"Name the following pictures.\"",
  "languagePictureNamingExaminerInstruction": "Compare the ability to name pictures with naming of real objects.",
  "languagePictureNamingAnomiaResponse": "Anomia: Cannot name picture.",
  "languagePictureNamingAgnosiaResponse": "Agnosia: Cannot describe object.",
  "languagePictureNamingResponseNormal": "All correct",
  "languagePictureNamingResponseEquivocal": "1 mistake",
  "languagePictureNamingResponseImpaired": "> 1 mistake",

