  "praxisLimbKineticTitle": "Limb-kinetic Apraxia",
  "praxisLimbKineticPatientInstruction": "\"Take this pen and rotate it with your fingers as fast as you can.\"",
  "praxisLimbKineticExaminerInstruction": "Test both hands.",

  "praxisIdeomotorTitle": "Ideomotor Apraxia",
  "praxisIdeomotorExaminerInstruction": "This is a failure to correctly position and move a limb in space. It can be assessed by asking the patient to mime tasks.",
  "praxisIdeomotorPatientInstruction1": "\"Show with your right hand how you would pour a cup of tea, add sugar and stir it.\"",
  "praxisIdeomotorPatientInstruction2": "\"Now do the same with your left hand.\"",

  "praxisIdeationalTitle": "Ideational Apraxia",
  "praxisIdeationalExaminerInstruction1": "This is the ability to correctly sequence a series of well-learned motor acts that lead to a goal. The patient is given an A4 sheet of paper, an envelope and a pencil.",
  "praxisIdeationalPatientInstruction": "\"Pretend that you have written a letter and would like to post it. Fold the sheet of paper so that it fits into the envelope, then seal the envelope and address it to yourself and then indicate where you will put a stamp.\"",
  "praxisIdeationalExaminerInstruction2": "The instructions can be repeated, as this is not a test of memory. Most individuals are able to do this task without any difficulty.",

  "praxisOralTitle": "Oral Apraxia",
  "praxisOralExaminerInstruction": "Oral apraxia is an inability to perform orobuccal movements.",
  "praxisOralPatientInstruction1": "\"Show me how you would blow out a match.\"",
  "praxisOralPatientInstruction2": "\"Lick crumbs from your lips?\"",
  "praxisOralPatientInstruction3": "\"Blow a kiss?\"",

  "praxisDressingTitle": "Dressing Apraxia",
  "praxisDressingExaminerInstruction": "This task involves limb-kinetic, ideomotor, and to some extent ideational praxis. It is assessed by asking the patient to put on a hospital gown or other suitable piece of clothing such as a cardigan. Observe if the patient is able to put their hands and arms through the sleeves correctly and is able to fasten the buttons.",

  "praxisLineDrawingTitle": "Line Drawing",
  "praxisLineDrawingExaminerInstruction1": "Line drawings are presented, and the patient is asked to copy them. The ability to successfully copy a line drawing depends on correct recognition of the drawing with visual processing. This input function is part of gnosis. Drawing with the dominant hand is an output function and part of praxis as it involves motor planning.",
  "praxisLineDrawingExaminerInstruction2": "The patient can be asked if their drawing resembles the stimulus drawing. If the patient says the drawing differs from the stimulus, but they do not know how to draw it correctly then it may indicate visual perception is intact but not higher order motor control.",
  "praxisLineDrawingPatientInstruction": "\"Copy these drawings.\"",
  "praxisLineDrawingScoringHeader": "Cannot name picture",

